DHCLIENT(8)                    System Manager's Manual                DHCLIENT(8)

NAME
       dhclient - Dynamic Host Configuration Protocol Client

SYNOPSIS
       dhclient [-4|-6] [-S] [-N] [-T] [-P] [-p port-number]
                [-d] [-e VAR=value] [-q] [-1] [-r] [-x]
                [-lf lease-file] [-pf pid-file] [-cf config-file]
                [-sf script-file] [-s server-addr] [-g relay]
                [-n] [-nc] [-nw] [-w] [-B] [-I dhcp-client-identifier]
                [-H host-name] [-F fqdn] [-V vendor-class-identifier]
                [-R request-option-list] [-timeout timeout]
                [-v] [--version] [if0 [...ifN]]

DESCRIPTION
       The Internet Systems Consortium DHCP Client, dhclient, provides
       a means for configuring one or more network interfaces using
       the Dynamic Host Configuration Protocol and the BOOTP Protocol.

       The DHCP protocol allows a host to contact a central server
       which maintains a list of IP addresses which may be assigned
       on one or more subnets. A DHCP client may request an address
       from this pool, and then use it on a temporary basis for
       communication on network.

OPTIONS
       -4     Use the DHCPv4 protocol to obtain an IPv4 address and
              configuration parameters (default).

       -6     Use the DHCPv6 protocol (not supported on LikeOS).

       -S     Use Information-request to get only stateless
              configuration parameters (i.e., without address). This
              implies -6 (not supported).

       -N     Restore normal address query for DHCPv6. This implies
              -6 (not supported).

       -T     Ask for IPv6 temporary addresses (RFC 4941). This
              implies -6 (not supported).

       -P     Enable IPv6 prefix delegation (RFC 3633). This implies
              -6 (not supported).

       -p port-number
              The UDP port number on which the DHCP client should
              listen and transmit. Default is port 68.

       -d     Force dhclient to run as a foreground process. Normally,
              dhclient will run in the foreground until it has
              configured an interface at which time it will revert
              to running in the background.

       -e VAR=value
              Define additional environment variables for the
              script that configures interfaces.

       -q     Be quiet at startup, suppress all terminal output
              except for error messages.

       -1     Try to get a lease once. On failure, exit with code 2.
              In DHCPv6 this sets the max duration of the initial
              exchange to timeout (from -timeout).

       -r     Release the current lease and de-configure the
              interface before exiting. After releasing the lease,
              dhclient exits. This is the opposite of the default
              behavior, which is to obtain a lease.

       -x     Stop the running DHCP client without releasing the
              current lease. Kills the existing dhclient process.

       -lf lease-file
              Path to the lease database file. Default is system
              dependent.

       -pf pid-file
              Path to the process ID file.

       -cf config-file
              Path to the dhclient configuration file.

       -sf script-file
              Path to the network configuration script invoked by
              dhclient when it gets a lease.

       -s server-addr
              Specify the server IP address or fully qualified domain
              name to transmit DHCP messages to.

       -g relay
              Set giaddr field of all packets to the relay IP address.
              This is useful for testing.

       -n     Do not configure any interfaces. Most useful combined
              with the -w flag.

       -nc    Do not drop capabilities. Normally, if dhclient was
              compiled with libcap-ng support, dhclient drops most
              capabilities immediately upon startup.

       -nw    Become a daemon process immediately (nowait) rather
              than waiting until an IP address has been acquired.

       -w     Continue running even if no broadcast interfaces
              were found. Normally will exit if it isn't able to
              identify any network interfaces to configure.

       -B     Set the BOOTP broadcast flag in request packets so
              servers will always broadcast replies.

       -I dhcp-client-identifier
              Specify the dhcp-client-identifier option to send to
              the DHCP server.

       -H host-name
              Specify the host-name option to send to the DHCP
              server. The host-name string only includes the client's
              hostname prefix.

       -F fqdn.fqdn
              Specify the fqdn.fqdn option to send to the DHCP
              server. This option cannot be used with the -H option.

       -V vendor-class-identifier
              Specify the vendor-class-identifier option to send to
              the DHCP server.

       -R request-option-list
              Specify the list of options the client is to request
              from the server. The option list must be a single
              string consisting of option names separated by commas.

       -timeout timeout
              Specify the time after which dhclient will decide that
              it's not going to be able to contact a server.

       -v     Enable verbose log messages.

       --version
              Print version number and exit.

EXAMPLES
       dhclient
              Obtain a DHCP lease on all interfaces.

       dhclient eth0
              Obtain a DHCP lease on eth0.

       dhclient -r
              Release the current lease.

       dhclient -x
              Stop dhclient without releasing the lease.

       dhclient -v eth0
              Obtain a lease with verbose output.

       dhclient -1 eth0
              Try once to get a lease.

       dhclient -H myhost eth0
              Request a lease with hostname "myhost".

SEE ALSO
       ifconfig(8), route(8)

